AB  - Myanmar is comprised of eight major ethnic groups: Bama/Myanma, Chin, Kachin, Kayin, Kayah, Mon, Rakhine, and Shan. In Myanmar's transition to democracy, each ethnic nationality plays a different role. The Bama/Myanma group is largely represented by the military, the ruling Union Solidarity and Development Party, and the main opposition party, the National League for Democracy. Though others do join the Bama/Myanma-led parties, most ethnic minorities either form or join other ethnic-based political parties. After rounds of meetings and negotiations, some noticeable progress has been made in the peace process. Nonetheless, challenges remain, including an evident lack of trust between the ethnic armed groups and the government, especially the military. Though efforts continue to be made toward a nationwide cease-fire, both sides have accused each other of trying to delay the peace process. On the other hand, Lian Sakhong, a NCCT member and a supreme council member of the Chin National Front, said, they are truly committed to peace. They're truly, truly committed to a national cease-fire agreement.
